Viatical-
From the latin word ''Viaticum'' which loosely interpreted means, "Preparation for a long journey". Today (2005), Viaticals are life insurance policies which are sold at a discount to the face amount, or death benefit, of people who have been medically determined to have life expectancies (L/E's) of less than two (2) years to live. These policies are sold to third parties usually unrelated to the insured, who also can be known as ''investors''. A life expectancy longer than two years, but less than eight (8) years is regarded as a ''Life Settlement'', or ''Senior Settlement''. The shorter the person's medically determined life expectancy (L/E), the more valuable (read: expensive) to the third party investor, the available viatical. Though viaticals have existed for hundreds of years, (usually a transaction between family members to keep poor Uncle Joe's life insurance policy from lapsing, thus saving the families inheritance), viatical's most recent iteration has been the practice of selling HIV positive patient's life insurance policies for the cash necessary to sustain life for their medical treatments to prevent the furtherance of AIDS and/or AIDS related symptoms.